  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legal history of money laundering prohibitions:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Initial anti-money laundering (AML) concepts emerged in the 1920s to combat organized crime\n- Targeted financial transactions associated with illegal activities like bootlegging and gambling\n\n2. United States Developments:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) first comprehensive federal AML legislation\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Established reporting and record-keeping requirements\n\n3. International Progression:\n- 1980s: Growing international recognition of money laundering as global financial crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n\n4. Major Legislative Milestones:\n- U.S. Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) significantly expanded AML regulations\n\n5. Modern Approach:\n- Comprehensive international legal frameworks\n- Increased focus on technological tracking\n- Expanded criminal penalties\n- Enhanced international cooperation\n\nThe legal framework continues evolving to address emerging financial technologies and sophisticated criminal techniques.",
